review.reviewBody:
Fits nicely into my large head (size L - head circumference 60-61cm). The fits is good and comfy. The helmet is light and feels agile. The head lamp retainer is ideal for a head lamp or goggles with a minimalistic strap. 
There are tons of ventilation and there is not a lot of insulation, which to me is ideal as I prefer to wear a binnie if it’s cold and keep it light when it’s warm.
review.name: Excellent!

review.reviewBody:
the ear covers are way smaller than they should be.
I'm at the bottom of the size M range and the ear protection isn't big enough to fully cover my ears. You can really feel the insufficient protection during windy or cold days.
I understand this helmet is not designed to be super warm. But at least make the liner big enough to protect the ears from wind!
I gave up on the liner with the ears and just started using the minimal liner it comes with and a cap instead.
The headlamp clips are also a joke. Did you even test snowboarding with a light during the testing phase?
review.name: Ear protection is jokingly small

review.reviewBody: This helmet fits me surprisingly well for its intended round head profile (husk prime fits better for my oval head better). That being said, if you're looking at this helmet you're here for a reason and this thing delivers. It is so light and breathes so well you practically forget about it. That being said, it is insulative enough to not have you feeling cold, but helps prevent you from overheating vs typical DH ski helmets. On cold/high wind/ inclement days you will want put your hood up, wear a skullcap, or both. I haven't used the warm weather liner yet or taken it biking or climbing, but for my ski days I am so pumped I picked this helmet over other options. :)
review.name: An excellent lightweight helmet

review.reviewBody: Love the weight, the different levels of insulation so you can swap out depending on the temperature, and feels very solid and good protection not only from the top but also the sides and back.  Appreciate the vents for the free air flow as well.
review.name: Great ski touring helmet

review.reviewBody:
I hate ski helmets, tried them all, they either don’t fit,too hot,can’t hear……
If only they could be like bike helmets- light comfy … all the things 
Well this one does the trick for me, forgot I  had it on.
I use it with the summer lining and either a headband, thin or thick beanie or baseball cap. So much more adaptable for piste or tour.  As a
Mountain Guide I’m pretty intolerant of kit that doesn’t work so really pleased.
review.name: Finally!

review.reviewBody: Salomon helmets have fit my head perfectly and their fit seems to be consistent among different helmets in their lineup.  I also bought the MTN Lab helmet, because I spend so much time touring and in 50/50 days with my wife and kids.  I could go with just the MTN Lab helmet for everything.  It’s light and comfortable also.
review.name: MTN Lab and Husk Prime MIPS

review.reviewBody: Having slightly prominent ears, I have struggled to find a helmet that doesn’t cause ear pain. I’ve just completed a week’s skiing wearing this helmet and have remained pain free. The combination of the design for round head shape and soft ear covers seems to have done the trick. My son wears hearing aids and has another Salomon helmet that works very well for him too.
review.name: Comfortable ears!

review.reviewBody: Please provide at least one high visibility colour choice.. ie. yellow, orange.  For backcountry safety, having a high visibility colour is important for search and rescue.
review.name: Great backcountry helmet

review.reviewBody: Recently got this to replace my climbing helmet to have a backcountry ski specific. I love this helmet!  It is lightweight, easy to carry and does the trick. Unfortunately my head is 55cm and I wish I had a medium instead of small for a little more wiggle room.  Consider sizing up if you are on the fence.
review.name: Super lightweight backcountry helmet

review.reviewBody:
The helmet space is pretty crowded these days. The Mtn Lab is a good lid for someone who prioritizes touring in their skiing, as the permanently open ventilation and swapable liners are better for that kind of rider. If you're mostly inbounds, then there are better options for you that will keep you warmer on the lifts.

Maybe you use your climbing helmet when skiing sometimes. But the reality is that climbing helmets, even the newer ones with the "ski mountaineering" certification, don't give you the same side impact protection that an alpine ski helmet offers. Being able to think, reason, recognize your loved ones, and go skiing are all things you could lose if you slam your melon into a tree or accidentally tomahawk through some rocks. The dual certification on this thing is a big reason to consider it. 

Does it weigh more than your climbing lid? Probably. But save the weight on your feet, not around your brain unless you've got pointy things on your feet and thousands of meters to ascend. 

I typically ski with a thin hat, ball cap, or balaclava under my helmet, and the MTN Lab in size Medium was right on the money. The adjustable cinch in the back should be standard on every lid. I swapped for the lighter liner immediately, but the ear pads could be nice. 

The headlamp catches on the sides are very nice, and prevent you from having to tape your lamp to your lid on after-dark exits. 

Someone in the comments said that this lid doesn't have a good goggle strap in the back, but the one that comes stock is great. Someone else asked for a light way to attach the helmet to their pack, and thankfully this one comes standard with a chin strap that many packs can grab onto. 

Only used it a few days thus far, so can't comment on durability, but I'm quite satisfied.
review.name: Touring focused, Inbounds capable.

name: MTN Lab Helmet

review.reviewBody: This saddle has a great shape. The "Arc" profile means the sides drop off a bit which is especially good for people who are a bit narrow and don't like to feel like they are sitting on a shelf where the sides of the saddle can dig into the back of your lower glutes. The cutout on this saddle is also great because unlike with some other saddles the area around the cutout is tapered a bit (why can't other companies figure that out?). The one thing this saddle could use to be perfect is just a bit more padding. I know there is a trend of making saddles hard as hell so you don't lose .038382 watts by being comfortably cushioned but come on. I checked out the Pro model with the Elaston as Specialized said it is supposed to be 26% softer or something. Yeah maybe if you have a 12" stack of it under a densitometer. But on the saddles where you have a 1/4'' of it under a thick rubbery cover, there is NO difference (and trust me on that, I would have happily paid the extra $115 for a softer version of this saddle). So, if you have tough sit bones this is a fantastic saddle but if you don't just make sure you have decent padding in your shorts. And just to through this out there, the rubbery saddle cover thing also needs to die. Most of us like to slide around a bit depending on the pace or grade. I know the manufacturers are probably looking for that elusive extra .000002 watt but I think the rubbery covers are probably being used because they are cheaper. I bet you these newer covers will also put a hurting on our expensive lycra bibs after a season.  Anyway, buy this saddle just tell the Big-S to pad it more.
review.name: Just needs a bit more padding

review.reviewBody:
Sit bone width 113
Saddle width 143

After spending a season on the Specialized Power Saddle, I found that there were some pressure points that developed for me over some of my longer rides. After a bit of research I found that the Specialized Power Arc saddle was specifically with a different curve than the original Power saddle. This means that if you want a Power saddle but you felt like the original power didn't fit well for you, then this is your answer. For me this was the case. I found that I was able to ride on this saddle more comfortably and for longer than I was able to ride on the sister saddle. I also found that by comparison, I lost none of the gains in power that the saddle allowed me to have. 

That being said, this still isn't a great long distance saddle. You're going to be much better off using the Romin saddle if you want a similar fit for anything longer than 70-80 miles of riding. 

The overall design of the saddle is perfect for allowing you to put down the power. The shape of the saddle in the rear is more flat, and the middle cutout makes it ideal for any type of riding, road, gravel or mountain. The shorter nose allows for more aggressive positioning when needed although you should note that you will likely need to make some fore and aft adjustments to your regular saddle position by comparison. 

Between this saddle and the Power Arc saddle, if you're on the hunt for a new seat, I firmly believe that you'll find a great fit on one or the other of the two after trying both.
review.name: Power refined

review.reviewBody: I was pointed to this saddle by a bike fitter from the standard power saddle. This worked for me. The "wings" don't flare out as much as the standard power saddle. This worked for me much better. Similar fit and cushion as the power saddle but with narrower "wing". I have one of these on each of my bikes.
review.name: Great Saddle

review.reviewBody: I've ridden tens of thousands of miles on the Specialized Romin, but was getting some hot spots while doing lots of trainer time during lockdown, and figured it was time to look for another saddle.  Of the Power saddles, the Power Arc is the one you want if you like the Romin.  I found the standard Power saddle unbearable.  Too flat across the sit bones for me.  But the Power Arc is much better; closer to the Romin, and my preferred saddle for trainer time and long days on the road.
review.name: The Power saddle for Romin users

name: Power Arc Expert Saddle

review.reviewBody: It's made with lightweight aluminum, looks good, and works even better. Shimano's entry into the dropper lever scene is all too late but I'm glad they're here. Worth every penny.
review.name: Best lever on the market

review.reviewBody: This is a great lever. It's bearing creates easy actuation. It's small and compact, but works better than my Wolf Tooth Light Action I have on another bike. The Wolf Tooth is a good lever, but Shimano's is just better. Don't let the small size fool into thinking it's not smooth or precise. I can easily lower the seat a few millimeters instead of the complete-drop-or-nothing action like the Wolf Tooth.  The Shimano replaced a push-down type lever on my bike.  Both that one and the Wolf Tooth are either on or off like a snap switch. It was difficult to lower the seat just a little bit.  The Shimano will easily lower the seat to any position, even while bouncing across a rock garden. The mounting screw is captive so it won't shoot across the garage floor into a black hole.  That same screw is used to adjust the rotational angle as well as lateral position.  It's so easy to get the right ergo setup.  Also, the small size does not hit my knee like the bigger Wolf Tooth.  After 5 rides of 30 miles or more, I'm convinced this lever needs to be on my other two bikes.  It comes with cable, housing with endcaps, and the aluminum crimp.
review.name: Converting all my bikes to this lever!

review.reviewBody:
Immediately out of the box I could tell this was a winner - incredibly smooth, breathable material and overall a very minimal look. I despise loud logos slapped everywhere (giordana, castelli) so was happy the iridescent Gore branding is both subdued and aesthetic on these bibs. Fit was perfect for me, just hoping the minimal straps don't stretch out...
Agree with other reviewer that where the front ends does slightly emphasize my tummy but it's not very constrictive so can live with that. Also prefer a shorter inseam but I'm not mad.
review.name: Super soft, sleek, minimal

review.reviewBody:
I love these bibs! The chamois is rad, great for long rides. I find the fit to be quite flattering; the fabric is buttery soft, the leg finish is smooth, so it does not constrict my leg and create the dreaded sausage leg. 

The one thing I would change is that the bib straps are quite flimsy; they're lightweight, laser cut Lycra with soft silicon gripper backing. They're so minimal that it almost makes the bib feel like you're wearing a short. While it's not uncomfortable, I do notice that when I'm riding the way the bib finishes in my mid-section... it kind of cuts in there and creates a bit of a pooch. But the fabric is so forgiving that this is ALMOST not an issue. I do prefer more traditional bibs that finish higher and have more support from the straps.

Updating those features (and maybe making the inseam 3" shorter, but I like short stuff) would give it a perfect 5. Truly, the fabric is otherworldly. 

The iridescent  heat transfer does start to crack and fade after only a few washes, but this doesn't bother me too badly.
review.name: Love them, almost perfect

review.reviewBody: These bibs are very thin and flimsy feeling. They might work great for crit racing or other cycling where you want everything extremely lightweight, and you will not have contact with material that might rub or touch your shorts. I was hoping these would be good long distance ride bibs, that I could occasionally take out on gravel, but they feel like the slightest piece of anything touching them would rip them to pieces. Additionally, the straps are narrow and uncomfortable, even just trying them on. I returned them.
review.name: Thin and flimsy

review.reviewBody: I have a couple of pairs of Gore C5 bibs that fit great, so I thought I'd like the C7 version. I ordered in large, which is the same size I have in the C5. The C7 seemed overall smaller -- legs were tight, waist too low, bibs a little short. The material is very thin, and I was worried I'd poke a hole in it trying to pull them up. The chamois seemed nicer than the C5s. For reference, I'm 5'11'', 150 and wear a large in other brands of shorts too (pearl izumi, giordana). I returned these without using in them.
review.name: Runs smaller than other Gore shorts

It's thick but breathable - perfect warmth under a mid-layer and shell layer for the chairlift, but wasn't ever too hot. The half zip is so nice to get more air in and not feel suffocated, and to zip up when it suddenly gets dark and cold.

review.reviewBody: Over the decades, I have bought 5 of these tops. and like everything, the style has evolved. This version is crazy long, larger than the size small I bought 3 years ago, sleeves are 2 inches longer and the neck is much bigger around. None of these changes work for me. Maybe it is a mis-labeled Medium? I'm assuming that since I have worn and washed it, it is not returnable so I will put it in the dryer and hope it shrinks.

review.reviewBody:
Just received my latest shirt - Twilight blue this time - in the mail and already wearing it. Comfortable, warm, perfect. I practically live in these during the winter months. Can always layer up as needed. I wore my other shirts two weeks ago in Yosemite and they kept me warm. 
My daughter bought my first shirt for a Christmas present years ago and it still holds up. Never thought I could wear wool, since I always had a sensitivity to it. But after that first one, I discovered this is not the case with Smartwool.
review.name: Love these for the winter months

review.reviewBody: I'm 5'4" and weigh 140lbs. My waist is about 28" and my chest is about 36". I ordered a medium and it's far too large. It won't work as a base layer. I'll have to return it. Besides the sizing issue, I liked this top.

review.reviewBody: I will start by saying that I knew these pants would fit weird based off all of the reviews. It really is such a shame, these rain pants have so much potential! I wear a size 16 and both XL/XXL in OR pants. I bought these in a 1x. The butt is tighter than I would like, the thighs are fine, and below the thighs are HUGE. It's very confusing- I don't think the large leg fit is to accommodate boots because they taper in slightly towards the bottom- it's around the knee that they're unnecessarily huge. Maybe they're designed for folks who wear knee pads or knee braces? It just looks and feels sloppy to me. My other big complaint is the waistband. The waist hits right around the belly button and is generous in size compared to the tight butt and hips but the shock cord (which probably contributes to making these pants more ultralight) is ineffective. I wish these had a more substantial elastic waistband or draw cord. I am an outdoor educator so I sit on the ground a lot while teaching and every time I sit down I have to hold them up so my butt doesn't show. As always with the Aspire goretex line, the quality, breathability and waterproofing are top notch without question!! If OR fixes these weird fit issues then these will be the best rain pants ever!
review.name: Weird fit!!!

review.reviewBody: This is the 2nd time I've bought these rain pants. I bought them in 2016, in a medium and they fit well and worked. I recently bought a new pair and am not happy at all. Pros: - fabric in theory is good quality Gortex - venting on sides is a nice feature - lightweight emergency layer CONS: - there are no belt loops or other ways to reinforce the fit on the waist - the fit is off, the lower leg and ankle area are huge - lack of front pockets - there is a tiny plastic widget that adjusts an elastic cord to cinch around your hips, its doesn't stay closed after cinching and therefore the pants don't stay put around your hips and ride down, leaving you uncomfortable, exposed, and cursing as you try to pull these pants up constantly doing (insert your fun activity here). After 3 days of testing these, I stopped packing them.
review.name: Stuck in the wet mountains with non-functioning rain pants

review.reviewBody: I've been using these pants where I work as a field biologist and have not been impressed. Everytime I wear them in moist grass or rain I end up wet. Just got back from a field with knee high moist grass, top off my pants and I'm soaked. Not impressed.
review.name: Not waterproof at all

review.reviewBody: They are my go-to in spring fall and winter. The wind proofing provides much warmth. I love OR products
review.name: Love love love these pants!

review.reviewBody: So light and comfortable I forget I'm wearing them! The very deep back pocket works well for a variety of things I might want to take with me.... My size medium fits comfortably over my other pants.
review.name: Love my Aspire Gore-Tex pants

review.reviewBody: I'm sure these pants would have functioned well; they certainly seem to be made well. However, I did not get an opportunity to test them, because the fit was very off. The waist and thighs fit like I expected, but, like some other reviews mentioned, the bottom of these pants are exceptionally wide. I know this is partly necessary to help get pants over shoes and whatnot, but this is over the top. I felt like I was tripping over myself, so I ended up returning them.
review.name: Fit is not right

review.reviewBody: Poor fit. Very baggy. Quite loose in the lower leg. Very thin.
review.name: Not quite right.

review.reviewBody: Firstly, I live in one of the rainiest places in North America, work outside, am in SAR, and spend much of my free time outdoors. So good rain pants are key. These are to replace my trusty Woods pair I'd had forever. First time with OR pants. Not sure what everyone was complaining about for fit? I'm 5'7", 140lbs, and 29" waist, and a medium fit perfectly. They're fitted but with space still to layer underneath or to tuck your boots inside of in heavy downpours. I think maybe everyone was expecting joggers or skinny pants or something but these fit like every other pair of rain pants I've ever had? Haven't used outside yet, but will update once I've done that!
review.name: Not sure why everyone is complaining?

review.reviewBody: These rain pants keep me dry, but they are quite wide in the leg area. I'm only 5'3" and skinny so they end up looking a little like clown pants...but I do stay dry!
review.name: Keeps me dry

review.reviewBody: These rain pants seem great. Not too tight in the hips. My only complaint is that they are pretty long/ loose at the bottom of the legs with no way to cinch them around the ankles. I haven't used them in heavy rain yet but they seem durable.
review.name: decent rainpants

review.reviewBody:
I purchased in the white color and thought it had a really classic look to it, which I liked. I am coming from a Giro helmet, which is a medium. I thought this Bell was on the bigger side despite the size range being the same as what I am currently wearing. Using the dial in the back cinched the helmet well nonetheless. The chin-closure buckle is unique, utilizing a magnet versus the much more common snap together buckle. 
I found it a little awkward but I'm sure if I kept it, I would have gotten used to it quick enough. However, I ultimately decided to return it because the manufactured label on the inside was dated Sept '21. review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: This shirt is SO warm and comfortable. The built in hood/mask is great. I wear it as my base layer skiing and it keeps me cozy, and covers my mouth / nose perfectly. My only complaint is the sleeves are a bit long so I fold them back for under my coat.

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: Made way too small I normally wear a medium and ordered a large so it would be loose fitting. I ordered it to take on a trip and it came at the last minute so I untangled and washed. Tried it on and it is too tight.
review.name: Runs way small.

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: Great base layer for hiking but stylish enough to wear around town. Great details include: 1- the hood has a slot for your ponytail, 2- zipping side pockets, 3- thumbhole to keep the sleeves down.
review.name: Warm, comfy and cute

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: Like some other comments have identified, this is a tighter fit so size up from your typical OR size. I am a 32B, 5'7", and 118 LBS and I got the size S and it fits perfectly. I wear this to go running and hiking, and I can fit a wool base layer underneath on very cold days. Perfect addition to my outdoor apparel.
review.name: Great fit

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: My wife had jaw surgery so her face is vulnerable to the cold and not only does the hoodies pony tail hole keep her hair out of her face but the built in neck and face protection has kept her comfortable on her runs. It has quickly become her go to running hoodie.
review.name: Feature Rich

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought this for visibility while running, but I think it will also be the perfect ski baselayer because of the gaiter/face mask and ponytail slot in the back. It's super warm but also lightweight, and the Sulfur color is gorgeous! I have really broad shoulders so I debated sizing up to a M or a L but ended up deciding on the M, and I'm happy with my choice. Yes, it's a fitted top but it's supposed to be. It hugs the top half with a little bit more of a flowy (but not baggy) fit at the bottom. The arms are long with thumbholes to help hold them in place. This is high quality, and they need to restock all the colors!
review.name: This will be the perfect ski baselayer

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: super tight, like a baselayer without much stretch, and weirdly long arms that are also tight. for reference i'm normally a women's small in most tops: 5'4", 34A bust, about 140 pounds, athletic build. This is tiiiiight and hard to get on. It'll work well in my "regular" size as a ski baselayer under my shell, but if you want this for running or don't want the super tight look, i'd size up. you'll have to roll the sleeves though.
review.name: weird fit

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: I took this backpacking and it was in the 30s at night. This kept me nice and comfortable throughout the night
review.name: Perfect winter layer

review.itemreviewed: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's
review.reviewBody: Tight and unflattering fit. I usually wear M or L on top - this is an L and feels restrictive even when worn on its own. I had hoped this would function as a mid-layer, but in practice it is more of a base layer. Biggest pro is the head and face coverage - great for cold weather sleeping. Not worth the weight for backpacking, but may keep around for cold weather car camping.
review.name: should have returned

name: Vigor Grid Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Women's

review.reviewBody: Okay this pack is not small or lightweight, but that is not why you buy a 100L pack.   I carried this pack with 33lbs over 16 miles.   It carries so well.  The way the shoulder pads/hip belt swivel helps to make carrying this pack amazing.   No soreness from the pack at all.  They also added heavier duty foam in the padding to help with heavier loads.   I LOVE this pack.
review.name: Comfort Load Hauler

review.reviewBody: The bag is as advertised+lifetime replacement! Roomy and simply perfect!
review.name: Excellent features

review.reviewBody: So close to being a great ruck! The downsides: 1) I'm between the Medium and Large - the Medium feels like a child's pack in every regard, the Large fits everywhere except the waist - no matter how tight I tighten it, it's just a smidge too loose! The adjustable waist strap is nice, but a little more velcro and I would think I could make this work 2) This ruck has the same fatal flaw sternum strap design as Osprey - from the first time using it, you can hear the sternum strap straining and squeaking - it DOES NOT stay put and constantly slides up - and I cringe waiting for it to pop off its rails or break altogether (the reason I dropped Osprey)... while carrying 50lbs. Other than the fit and the horrific sternum strap design, this is THE most comfortable ruck I've ever put on. When it comes to 100L+, I've recently tried Osprey (terrible sternum strap), Mystery Ranch (terrible shoulder straps that constantly slip and need adjusted), and the Gregory Denali with sternum straps that stay in-place but have a metal on fabric design that just destroys itself after 50 or so miles. Back to the Baltoro - this would be a great pack if they had more overlap in sizes and implemented a more robust sternum strap that would stay put and not be subject to failure (you don't realize how important the sternum strap is until it breaks on Day 2 of a 10-day trip!).
review.name: So close, but not close enough

review.reviewBody: Great backpack.  Love all the space and access to it.
review.name: Great Backpack

review.reviewBody: I really loved the look of these and they fit comfortably but when I’d walk, my toes would fall over front edge of shoe like other reviewers said. I unfortunately had to return them. Still a Teva fan though !

review.reviewBody: I really love the bed of the shoe, it's comfortable. And the addition of the flaps that protect from blistering is really nice. But I have no idea why they'd get rid of the strap that goes over the top of your ankle. My foot slides all the way to the front and my toes almost are hanging off because there's nothing to really hold my foot in place. If it had that strap, it'd be perfect. But I slightly regret this purchase:/ I also really wish they had half sizes, an 8 was too big and this 7 feels just not perfect. A 7.5 would've been nice.

review.reviewBody: My favorite pair this summer. If I could wear them everyday I would. Very stylish and cozy!

review.reviewBody: ...and they were so close! The soles are great, the lining on the inner straps is a lifesaver for bone spurs, and I love the buckle closure. And I love the monochromatic look in fun colors. Sadly, as others have reported, the fit is just off. Even with straps uncomfortably tight, there's no way to keep my foot from sliding forward and off the front edge of the sandal while walking. And that's just walking around my house. If you can fix the fit issues I'm guessing these will fly off the shelves.
review.name: I wanted to love these...

review.reviewBody: I wear these when I need to walk about and want support and comfort. This is my third pair, all just alike but color. I love these in lite blue, very stylist and looks great with jeans.
review.name: Best sandles for walking

review.reviewBody: A little bulky but feels sturdy! True to size and also had room to wear with socks too if you adjust the straps! Love!

review.reviewBody: Too heavy and wide for women. I returned the shoes.
review.name: No

review.name: I prefer original or ampsole hurricane

review.reviewBody:
I have bunions on both feet.  My Cotopaxi Teva sandals are obsolete as this condition has progressed but I don’t want to give up hiking in my Tevas!!  I have had the Hurricane Verge sandals for almost two months and I adore them ( especially the lilac color, SWEET!). The pads everywhere give me the experience of a open air, cushy cloud on my feet.
In the cart right now I have my second pair ready to order.  I will have a pair for dress and a pair that can go in the mud, the grass, the salt, wherever.  I recommend, especially for wide or bunion-ized feet.
review.name: Quite Pretty & Cool

review.reviewBody: I’ve had this for about a month and I’ve already bought two more. This is light, warm, and has a perfect for me. Even the next fits when fully zipped. I am 5’10” 165lbs and snagged a small. The zipper allows for easy on/off and I appreciate that there is no hood. The absence of a hood keeps weight and cost down yet it leads to easier layering. This shirt is fine on its own in 30° active pursuits and gets warmer if you cover it with a wind jacket. Covering the fleece will lead to a longer log because it is a very soft material that can snag when the inevitable bushwhacking begins.
review.name: Great Piece of Gear

review.reviewBody: Lighter but warmer than expected. Can tell it will be great for a mid layer out in the cold.
review.name: Extremely please

review.reviewBody: I don't like heavyweight fleece layers, and when running errands in and out of stores, I like to wear a lighter jacket so I don't melt in a store. Future fleece pairs well with the lighter jacket to maintain a comfortable level of warmth for those situations. The same concept goes with my morning walking layers when temperatures drop into the teens or higher single digits. Future fleece is a versatile layer and I own several pieces with and without the hood. Future fleece is a comfortable option for me
review.name: Super Light Weight Layer

review.reviewBody: Didn't really know what to expect since this was my first time buying "FUTUREFLEECE". Assumed it was like any other fleece but I am glad I was wrong. The material is much more lightweight allowing for easier layering. The material is deceiving thin but is as warm all the other fleece jackets I've owned. Definitely would recommend to friends, family or anyone looking for a lightweight fleece option.
review.name: Exceeded expectations!

review.reviewBody: I bought as a gift for my son-in-law. It fit perfectly and looked fantastic on him. He said it was the perfect weight.
review.name: Great fleece

review.reviewBody: This is a perfect middle ground, And a perfect midlayer. Light and breathable enough to be comfy once the sun pops out on those early mornings. Snug and warm enough the make a difference so you don't have to through that true cold weather layer on.
review.name: A smart and balanced midlayer.

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I like how comfortable the Summit LT 1/2-Zip is. It's super thin so definitely wear as a base layer when it's cold outside. I've had my FutureFleece for a little over a month and I already see it fraying on the belly area. The times that I've washed it, I washed it inside out and I always let it air dry. For the price I paid for it I would like it to be better quality.
review.name: I don't know if I would spend over $100 to buy it again

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] this futurefleece is very nice material -comfortable and well designed cut. bought specifically for another upper mid-layer for skiing in mid-winter. attempted using over the Summit Series Crevasse ½-Zip, but getting the layers to play nice wasn't working -there was no easy way to not have the sleeves not get turned around one another. i tried using it this way everyday for about a week before giving up on that particular layering system. don't get me wrong, this item is super nice, but until i am willing to try it as the base layer i am not sure where it fits into the system as layering on top of other items proved frustrating. no way i wasn't keeping the item as i am sure i will find it's place. sized up from the sizing table one level as i was looking for mid layer and it fits perfectly.
review.name: this futurefleece is very nice material

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This is one of the best piece I've bought! It's super lightweight yet keeps me warm, perfect for traveling/hiking.I bought another crew neck after this. The only thing I would recommend is to wear another short sleeve inner layer as the fleece material could be a little bit scratchy on bare skin (just a little bit, no big deal).
review.name: So light yet so warm!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I love this Future Fleece Pullover for trail hiking. It's great as a mid-layer on cool mornings under a lightweight jacket and as an outer layer when the morning sun's up.
review.name: Verstaile warmth

review.reviewBody:
Bought this bun after a lot research, looking for alternatives to my wobbly Maxxis DHF [which I have been running on the rear]. It seemed to fit the bill, so I went ahead and bought it. I had it sitting for a few months, until my DHF finally reached its end.

I spooned it on less than a week ago and finally took it out for its maiden voyage this afternoon. 3 miles of climbing later, on the top of the ridge, it was time for the fun part. Not even 50-60 meters down the trail and BOOM! Cataclysmic blowout. I examined the tire trailside, and found a pretty large, L-shaped puncture between two tread blocks. The puncture was large enough that not even three bacon strips shoved in would seal it.

This is my training loop, and I’ve ridden it probably 100+ times. Never had any kind of flat, anywhere. When the tire failed, I actually wandered back up the trail to see if there was any errant broken glass or some kind of litter anywhere. Was it possible? Surely. Was it likely? Probably not… it is a well-ridden trail and dozens of bikes are on it at some point every week. The area was rocky and loose, but it’s not like I was riding down a bunch of sharpened flint. Again, this is a trail with which I am very familiar, so it’s not like there is anything unexpected.

Could it have been a rock? Maybe. Were my tires over/under inflated? Nope. I run my rear tire pretty firm… 26-28 lbs. Today was no different. Again, NEVER had a flat on this trail. I’m also running Huck Norris inserts, for good measure. I mean, it could just have been the perfect storm of circumstances… unsure. But in the end, it was a long walk back to the car.

Looks like I’m going back to the old Maxxis wobble. I’ll take it over a big puncture any day. I don’t think I’ll trust a Vittoria anytime soon.
review.name: Absolute Tire Failure

review.reviewBody:
I'm a big fan of Vittoria. I've been on the same 2 Morsa for oven a year. Ran the center tread gone on the rear. Not a single flat. Rarely had to add much air. I ride a lot. Multiple times a week here in SLC and Park City. So when it was time replace my tires, I went with the 2.4 Mazza in the front. I moved the Morsa in the front to the back and will replace it with another Morsa if they are not all gone soon. Grip is great on these. A nice front tire on my SB4.5c. 

This 2.4 mazza is a little narrower to the same width at best (brand new) as my 2.3 Morsa after 1 year.
review.name: Big Fan

review.reviewBody: Been riding minions for too long, trying something new. These tires do not degrade in the same way as Maxxis, very important for me because I went through 3 rear tires this year. No cutaway wear under the supports, very limited wear all over after 300 miles of hard riding, grip is great on Utah loose over hard terrain. Running XC mazza front and rear on a 150/140 travel rig. No way around it, these tires have been much better. Price, durability, and not having to trash them after a few weeks of riding, 100% buy!
review.name: So good!

review.reviewBody:
I've been riding this tire for a few months now and I am super happy with it. Yes, it does resemble another well known tire on the market, I can live with that. 

Overall, this tire rolls decently well for a large lugged tire. Cornering traction is excellent in all conditions I have encountered (hard pack, loose over hard, dust, gravel) and there is plenty of braking traction too. This tire is great as a front tire and would also work well as a rear for more aggressive riders. 

I wouldn't recommend this tire for an XC riding but it is perfect for trail and enduro style riding. The weight is inline with tires that have a similar construction. The trail casing is stiff and allows you to run low pressures without worrying about sidewall squirm while cornering. I find I run between 17-20 PSI depending on the trail conditions.

If you dare to try new this is an excellent alternative to other more common tires on the market.
review.name: Traction everywhere

name: Mazza XC-Trail 29in Tire

review.reviewBody: Great looking. Super comfortable. Great traction on deck.  Only negative is they will run the skin raw at the Achilles. Have to wear socks.

review.reviewBody: I have size 13EE feet, and finding a decent boat shoe is harder than it might seem. I have worn some version of traditional leather or leather-and-mesh products all my life, and bought a pair of these shoes when they came on sale, just to see. I'll never go back. These shoes fit very well - close like a good pair of gloves, yet flexible and unrestrictive. They are well-made, lightweight, breathable, easy to clean up, and they provide excellent traction on deck. While I am a VERY traditional guy where style is concerned, I bought the orange shoes with the dark sole, and I love them. Now, MY ONLY WISH IS THAT THE ORANGE SHOES WITH THE DARK SOLE COULD BE RE-INTRODUCED; I'd buy a couple more pair straightaway if I could find 'em!
review.name: LIFE GOT BETTER

review.reviewBody: Feels great and very lightweight. Little irritation on the back of my upper heal when wearing a low sock so I recommend wearing a sock high enough to cover your ankle area above the shoe. After wearing a higher sock I could not ask for a more comfortable shoe.
review.name: Lightweight and comfortable

review.reviewBody: Wore this shoe for 3 straight days Tarpon fishing out of Key West. I’m are on the water for over 8 hours with my guide. These shoes have great padding for standing all day during some choppy water due to the wind. We had some rain on two of my days and they had great grip. By far the best boat shoe I’ve ever owned. I’ve tried several name brands, and at the end of along day of fishing you can’t wait to just get off your feet. Not the case with these shoes. Great job!!!
review.name: Great shoe

review.reviewBody: I have had these several months now and love them, not just for fishing but casual wear too!  I wish they would put these SUPER COMFORTABLE SOLES on short boots too!!!!
review.name: Super Comfortable and Versitile

review.reviewBody:
I've only put a few rides on them but I have read such good reviews from notable cycling blogs and websites that I'm sure they will stand up over time. Upon first look they strike a remarkable resemblance to another very popular MTB tire (the Maxxis DHF). Is this a good thing or a bad thing? Maybe both? The good thing is that the DHF are one of my all time favorite tires and these Kessels seem like they are even chunkier and grippier in certain types of terrain. The bad? Well the price is pretty much the same and with tires you usually want to go with the more notable, reliable and quality controlled option (in this case the Maxxis brand). 

That being said, I think these will be a great tire and I like the sizing and availability right now in the gumwall 2.5s. Yes they may be somewhat of a "knockoff" but they are a super high quality one and I think it can't hurt to have a healthy competition in the tire marketplace, considering Maxxis pretty much has a monopoly on the MTB tire game. Excited to put more miles on these and see how they compare to my tried and true DHFs.
review.name: Decent alternative to Maxxis

review.reviewBody:
This is exactly what I was looking for in a car camping pad. The pad itself is filled with air and a thin layer of foam. Significantly more comfortable than any air mattress that I have slept on. The pad packs down small enough that I can fly with it when needed. 

The pad will self inflate a decent amount in about 15 minutes. Then you can easily use the air sack that it comes with to add air to it. The air sack is pretty unique to Nemo and I love it. You blow a little air into a sack and squeeze the air out the other end - much easier than blowing directly into a pad. 

Deflating takes more effort than a more compact pad but still not bad - I roll it up once to get the air out after letting it self deflate a bit. Then I do it one more time to push any residual air out and that’s usually good enough.
review.name: Easy to set up, tear down and is comfortable

review.reviewBody:
This was so awesome. If it weren’t for my kids in the tent with me I would have had the perfect sleep. So easy to inflate, stays inflated and is sooooooo dang comfy. 
I’ll be pulling this out for company as well as using it in the tent. I’ve never been camping and not felt the ground. This was a game changer. 
Thanks for a great sleep!!
review.name: Slept on a cloud!

review.reviewBody: We just love this air mattress! Great nights sleep. No aches when waking up!!
review.name: Roamer Double Mattress

review.reviewBody: From a very picky sleeper, this pad is as good as a top-quality mattress.  It doesn't feel like it a an air mattress, thanks to the cellular structure. It took a while to self-inflate the first time out of the bag. I eventually pumped in some air. It works great now. Very easy to stow away, and very light.
review.name: Very comfortable

review.reviewBody: This mattress is more comfortable than the mattress I use for a bed, and can be inflated or deflated to customize the comfort for different body types. Soft and strong, it's the second one I'm buying, as my son "borrowed" the first one for an indefinite period. If you have cats, do not let them scratch the mattress. Otherwise it is very sturdy.
review.name: Comfortable and long-lasting

review.reviewBody: This couple owns the double and it is the most comfortable camping mattress built for two. An added bonus is that the soft face fabric is quiet which allows your partner to sleep even if you are a restless sleeper. Fits perfect in our 3 person tent for a great glamping experience.
review.name: Quiet and comfortable

review.reviewBody: Turn camping on the hard ground into Glamping. This mattress is so comfortable and insulates well from ground heat loss. I expect years of use from NEMO! It is large inflated so make sure you have room but does stow in the bag easily.
review.name: Turn that hard ground into Glamping!

review.reviewBody: I’ve tried a LOT of different pads and the Roamer is by far the most comfortable and warmest I’ve slept on. It is heavy but that’s to be expected of a true luxury sleeping pad. I’ll take the weight in exchange for the comfort any day!
review.name: Roamer, sleeping bliss!

review.reviewBody: It takes a bit to blow this up, but seems pretty solid once it's ready. Definitely a step up from the old 1 inch thick pad.
review.name: A step up!

review.reviewBody: Excellent mattress, a little big for backpacking but great for car camping and or scouting. Very comfortable and easy to inflate.

review.reviewBody:
Jacket has performed beyond expectations!

I purchased this jacket to use for downhill Skiing, with the expectation that i would use it in more mild temperatures. I live in the NWT, Canada where temperatures can reach as low as -50C. more often than not i find myself reaching for this jacket (layering during colder temperatures) for most of my winter activities!

This jacket has great waterproofing and breathability & very good and breaking the chill from the wind. i would recomend this jacket to anyone who is active in the winter at a range of temperatures as it is very easy to layer up underneath. 

10/10

review.reviewBody: Jacket has held up well, for 5 years, with regular use, size is slightly small for the rating.

I’m 6’2 and about 255lbs slightly muscular build. I usually wear XL for shirts and sweaters. The XL for the Microgravity AscentShell fit me very well. I have room for a layer underneath but it will be trim with not a lot room left. The arm length is perfect for me! I’m excited to try it out in the wild.

Then a few weeks later I used it in Olympic NP, when it rained a lot during the memorial weekends, but the jacket managed to keep me dry inside. Only little complaint would be the slim fit - it fits me well for the waist and makes me look sharp, but the clothes hem is a bit too tight, sometimes I feel it restrained my ability to move. It will be awesome if it can a double zipper to adjust it

review.reviewBody:
I've owned a number of highly technical jackets from various suppliers over the past 20+ years including Marmot; Patagonia, North Face, a Berghaus or 2 (UK) and Jack Wolfskin (Germany) in all types of weather.  My primary use has been hiking and urban exploration.  I cannot really fault any of these jackets as they all performed adequately when I used them sensibly.  But there have been a couple of times things went rather badly.  Auschwitz-Berkenau is one cold mother in Mid-Winter and the Scottish Highlands can be quite challenging as well.  I've learned to layer, especially if doing some urban traipsing in and out of shops in cold weather where outside temps are below freezing but stores have the heat cranked up to just under cremate.

But I've said all of that  to say this-  You absolutely cannot go wrong with RAB down jackets for light weight warmth with great breathability.  My first RAB was the Electron Pro with 800 fill down.  It finally gave up the ghost after around 5 years of heavy use and being tossed about rather unceremoniously.  I tried a Patagonia Down Sweater Jacket and while it was warm, it shed down like crazy.  Never really had much of a problem with that using the RABs.  I purchase this RAB Mythic Down Jacket a couple of weeks ago and while I can't speak to its long-term durability, man is it ever sweet!  So light & warm!  Blocks the wind very well and is an awesome fit that allows me to throw on a light rain shell over it if it starts to pour.  Yes, it is expensive but given my history with RAB, I'm convinced it is well worth the money.  If you prefer a little looser fit, the Electron is also a great choice.  Either way, you'll have less need for multiple layers in most instances with a RAB 800/900 fill Down jacket.

I'll try and update some in a few months once it's been given a proper workout, but I could not be more pleased thus far!  I honestly believe RAB is at the forefront of Down Insulated technical jacket production & takes a back seat to no one, not even Canada Goose!
review.name: GO WITH RAB

review.reviewBody: This jacket has super loose stitches, down leaks constantly. Also, this has some of the least durable 10d nylon I've ever felt. My ghost whisperer has better durability than this jacket does. The only reason I even gave it a 3 star is its super warm.
review.name: Horrible stitching, terrible durability.

review.reviewBody:
Despite what a backcountry rep told me, and despite what the Shimano GRX 400 docs say (by omission), these pads, which are the L04C metallic pads, fit my GRX 400 brakes.  My GRX 400 brakes came new with the L03A resin pads, so if your bike uses L03A pads, then these L04C pads will also fit.

Oh yeah, and if you don't already know, the "L" on a pad means the left side of the caliper when you are sitting on the bike, and  the "R" on a pad means the right side of the caliper.
review.name: Shimano GRX 400 brakes
comment: These do fit in my GRX810 brakes, but, they are super tight, and are super squeeky.  They definitely don't "grab" as well as the L03A pads, but, will last significantly longer.  It requires a significant amount of brake adjustment to get these to work correctly.

review.reviewBody: I needed a fast rolling tire for riding mostly rocky hard pack trails with some loose rocks. I have been riding Maxxis DHF/DHR on my Niner Rip 9.  I found these and look at some reviews.   I put the 29"x2.5"  on tubeless and loved them for my riding tail conditions. They are fast rolling and side knobs are large enough to handle good in turns and through technical rock sections. I got the durable since I get a lot of sidewall cuts.   I am really enjoying these wheels front and back.
review.name: Digging these Teravail Ehline Tires 29

review.reviewBody:
I had been running Maxxis Ardent Races and Ikons on my XC bike for two sets of tires (both 2.2"), and wanted to try something a little meatier, so I rolled the dice with these Ehlines (both front and rear).  I put a 2.5" in the front and a 2.3" in the rear, both are the Light and Supple model.  

They mounted easily on my DT Swiss X1700 rims.  I used Stans sealant, and the rear doesn't seem to be losing air at all, on the front, the air loss is normal (1-3 psi a week?).  

The front tire measures 2.38" wide and the rear is 2.2" wide on my rims (22.5mm i.w.) after about six weeks at ~22psi.   Teravail says the ideal rim internal width for these tires is 25mm, but the tire shape is fine on my 22.5mm rims.  So they're materially narrower than stated on my rims, and I think they'd run narrow on 25mm i.w. rims as well.

I've done ~20 rides on these tires so far on varied terrain.  I put 22psi in the front and 24psi on the rear, and these tires have made a big difference on my bike.  Yes, they are slightly higher volume than the Maxxis tires they replace, but these Ehlines feel more supple, and there was a very noticeable improvement in the overall suspension effect on the bike.  The biggest difference is how much more confident I am in rougher terrain, and the bike sticks to the trail better in corners than the Ardent/Ikons.  The tires grip better in rooty/rocky technical terrain, too.  Yes, this comes with a small weight penalty, and maybe a small rolling disadvantage compared to the small block Maxxis tires, but I only race a handful of times a year, the rest of the time I do long XC style trail, so this tradeoff works for me.

Assuming these tires hold up well, I plan to stick with this brand/model long term.
review.name: Made a difference on my bike

review.reviewBody:
Super stable saddle bag if packed correctly (just like any other saddle bag). The cradle system is really nice if you put heavier objects in first.

Stuffing the bag took some finesse as the narrow end is hard to pack into if you have larger hands. The bag extends back past the cradle, so if you have heavier objects closer to the rolltop side, it's bounce around a lot. I also noticed this if the things I'm packing end exactly at the cradle. For example, my sleeping bag can pack in first, but ends up right at the end of the cradle. If I put clothes in next, then the clothes can bounce around as the only stability that end gets is from the compression strap. Just have to pack it smartly and it's all good.

Didn't love that the bag secures with the same strap that attaches the cradle to the seatpost. A minor inconvenience if you're taking the bag off at the end of each day. I typically just loosened the straps and kept the bag in the cradle so it wasn't a deal breaker.

review.reviewBody:
I took this on a 21 day trip to Nepal and up to Everest Base Camp. I treated about 10-12 liters a day and had to swap out batteries after about 15 days. I was using Energizer Lithium Ultimate batteries for the trip and I think I got the expected life out of them. 

I wish 2 things were different:
1. I wish that there was an indicator light on the top, or somewhere else visible, to indicate that it was working or that it had failed because I pulled it out of the water. Its current placement makes it difficult to see the red LED because it's submerged in the water and impossible to see thru a Nalgene covered in stickers. Same goes for the UV wand itself.. very difficult to see except for when indoors or once the light got low in the sky. 
2. The offset/asymmetrical wand cover made it difficult to operate in the dark or by feel. Chances of breaking the wand would also decrease if the wand was centered instead of off-centered. 

Neither of us got sick from anything waterborne so all in all it was a big win.
review.name: Pretty darn good

review.reviewBody: Worked great for treating water. No chemicals, worked every time I needed to treat water. Highly recommend over drops.
review.name: Light, compact and never failed

review.reviewBody: I've used my SteriPEN on trips including all-day climbs (Snakedike on Half Dome), week-long family backpacking trips, and months-long international trips to Micronesia. I haven't gotten sick once, though I have had to resort to boiling water and/or using chemicals (MSR's AquaTabs) when my SteriPEN's batteries wore out prematurely. Used according to the instructions, I have high confidence in the efficacy of the device. It's fast, convenient and light (lighter than anything other than chemical treatments, as far as I've found). The problem is that the batteries are expensive, hard to come by in most small US towns, and completely unavailable in many remote international places. Worse, in my experience, I found the number of treatments for every 2 batteries (the SteriPEN requires 2 cr123, 3.0 volt batteries) to be highly variable and strongly affected by cold temperatures. Note that reduced water clarity will have a substantial effect on treatment efficacy! In a pinch, you can let your water sit over-night to let suspended sediments settle out. It's a pain, but better than getting sick. I still rely on my SteriPEN, but I'm careful to check the condition of the batteries before heading out, and pack extras as well as AquaTabs. One other note: You essentially HAVE to use a wide-mouth 1 liter Nalgene as your water bottle--anything else is impossible to use with the SteriPEN or so difficult as to compromise the water treatment you're getting. I like using a hydration pouch for many outdoor activities, and this imposes an additional hassle, weight and volume.
review.name: Fantastic...with important caveats

review.reviewBody: My favorite outdoor climbing shoe. Is exceptional on sandstone crack. Great fit and comfortable.
review.name: Scarps Mid Generator

review.reviewBody:
I am a long time sasquatch of modest accomplishment - sport up to easy 5.12, trad to 5.10, very occasionally 5.11. 6'2", 205 lbs, size 14 street shoe. 

I wanted a shoe that I could wear for many pitches at a time, and for desert routes with sustained foot and toe jamming. Most climbing shoes feel very soft to me, and quickly disintegrate, so stiffness and durability are desirable. The Sportiva TC Pro fit the bill but the largest size made was too tight a fit. The Evolv Yosemite Bum didn't fit me at all. Scarpa makes their shoes up to Sasquatch sizes, so I bought the Generator V size 47 with a snug, toes-slightly-curled fit. 

They offer a similar out of box stiffness and overall demeanor as the TC Pro. Breaking them in took forever - at first they felt like climbing in ski boots. They're the only climbing shoes that ever needed to break in around my arch, not toes or heels. After six months of desert cracks, multi-pitch routes, granite face climbing, they've become an all time favorite shoe. After stretching about a half size, the clunky, loose-feeling heel and tight arch have relaxed, my toes are all but flat, and their stiffness means I have yet to lace the front of the shoe tightly. 

The stiffness allows me to climb 150 feet of desert foot jams in comfort. The high ankle, padded uppers, and extensive rubber make for fantastic jamming, particularly in thin hands cracks and up. For jam cracks in Indian Creek they're amazing! Hand size and bigger, it's hard to imagine anything better. Obviously in tighter cracks their bulk becomes a liability. They are far less sensitive than most shoes, but they stick to all sorts of stuff - they performed admirably on a (TR) lap on Etude at Suicide, an insecure 11a tips crack. 

The recurring theme of this shoe is: insensitive, yet sticks to everything. 

This is not a shoe for sport climbing, bouldering, and gym climbing. It is fantastic for medium to wide cracks, all day foot jamming, fist cracks, offwidths, long trad routes that torch your ankles and calves with hanging belays, and they climb shockingly well once you're used to the totally different experience from softer, lighter shoes. 

After beating on these shoes for a full year they're at the cobbler for a resole. The rand, upper, laces, and leather are in fantastic shape, I can't wait to get them back because they'll be better than new. Needing a trad shoe while they're gone I actually bought a second pair, that's how much I like them. I am so impressed by their durability and construction - I am extremely hard on shoes.

Pros:
* Fantastic foot protection in foot jams and wide cracks
* Excellent jamming down to thin hands and decent below
* Excellent edging, good smearing
* Relatively comfortable once broken in
* Very durable sole, rand, laces, upper

Cons:
* Extremely insensitive. These are stiff - and I never say that! 
* Very long break-in period. Think months. They break in more like a hiking boot than a climbing shoe, as the shoe molds not just to your toes but to your arch and heel as well.
* Very heavy in your pack or on your harness. They weigh twice as much as slippers!
* Warm with so much rubber and padded uppers
* Poor performance on steep routes and pockets. 
* The tongues delaminate! This is a silly oversight as the tongues are two pieces of scrim laminated over breathable foam, and the bits delaminate. A few stitches would solve the problem - indeed, the velcro version, the Generator V, have stitched tongues. Fix this, Scarpa! 

Expensive, but similar to other high end shoes

Overall, highly recommended for their intended purpose. Medium to wide jam cracks, trad routes, vertical terrain. I can't imagine anybody needs to be told this but these are not a good option for gym or sport climbing, bouldering, overhangs or anything like that.
review.name: Crack Climbing Monsters

review.reviewBody:
Wearing size 49 means that I can't be cool like all my friends and wear TC Pros.  I have limited options but had found that the maestro mid eco was about the best all around shoe I could find.  
 The maestro really seemed like it was supposed to be quite similar to the TC Pro.  Scarpa then discontinued it and told me that the generator would replace it.  It is a very different shoe though.  The Generator is stiffer, heavier and has quite a different toe box.  The toe box feels like it's designed to have your toes flatter because it's quite wide and doesn't point your toes together - however the toe end of the shoe has little vertical volume which still forces your big toe to not be flat.  The heel is really padded - which is great for offwidth I imagine, but honestly they didn't seem like shoes I would want to jam in or spend all day in.  I broke it in for a while at the gym and then took it outside.  After a three pitch trad route my feet weren't that happy, and I never trusted my feet that much at the gym.  My feet are big so I really need flat toes to jam and the stiffness feels too much to really be able to work them into a non perfectly straight crack.  The stiffness is also a bit much for slab.  So then that kinda leaves just edging and the toe setup isn't quite right for that either.  The good thing is that because I have narrow feet often times with laces the edges with the lace holes almost touch, these at least there is room to tighten further.  For me I'll continue to search for a better option.  For me at least the helix is better for slab and all day trad even though it's pretty compromized and doesn't fit great.   For the gym and sport, the fiveten niad with laces is a better performance shoe.  Scarpa please bring back the maestro mid eco!
review.name: Maestro's replacement disappointed me

review.reviewBody: This is a very versatile jacket.  For temps in the 48-60 degree F range, I wear a thin long-sleeve baselayer.  For temps from 38-50, I wear a baselayer and a lightweight Smartwool turtleneck.  For reference, I ride in Zone 2 or higher with an average distance of about 45 miles.  I start out uncomfortably cold, but warm up in 2-6 miles.  At the higher end of either range, I can ventilate with the two-way zipper and chest vents as much or little as I need to.  I have jackets, vests, and arm warmers for different days to tailor my rides to various conditions wind and humidity factor in to comfort.  I am 6 feet tall, 185 lbs, and XXL fits great with room for these layers.

review.reviewBody: I ordered this jacket in XL and XXL. For reference I’m 5’11” 182 lbs fit cyclist.  Im not the classic skinny arm guy for a cyclist and that’s the biggest problem I had.  The XL fit pretty good other than the sleeves which were too tight.  The XXL was too big in the chest and shoulders.  The quality of the garment is pretty good.  Just not for me.  I ended up with the Endura Windchill 2 jacket which has many of the same features and frankly for my money is better all the way round.  I ordered the L and XL in the Endura jacket and could’ve gone either way.  Settled on the XL so I can layer underneath more comfortably.

review.reviewBody: Very pleased - bought these for a longer distance ride with good climbing.  The shorts are super comfortable and fit very well.  Love all Castelli products!

review.reviewBody: I bought these in full confidence and support for previous Castelli shorts. I wore them twice on the trainer (they are tight!) and then braved them out on the road. Immediately when exposed to the elements (the summer heat), the logo started to peel. I am unhappy with these, but have worn them and it’s been over a month so I am stuck with them. Will stick to brands with better results for the miles I put into cycling shorts.
review.name: Poor quality

review.reviewBody: I tend to like Castelli shorts, but not all work for me. I tended to buy free aero shorts. These are just as good. I am not rail thin. I have a female cyclist's body. I ride a lot.
review.name: Buying another pair

review.reviewBody:
The castelli chamois is so nice, but the waistband is just too constrictive. I have a 28 inch waist and ordered a M, which should've given me plenty of clearance, but there was no chance. I couldn't stand being in these longer than 30 seconds.

Also, no one seems to be mentioning how squeaky these are. Like any leg movement causes the seams to squeak--I think it's the reflective material on the back that's doing it. Not something I've ever encountered before...
review.name: Squeaky Seams, Tight Waistband

review.reviewBody: Sized up per previous review. Overall I love these shorts, the fabric, waistband, leg grippers and chamois are awesome and super comfortable. The catch is that the seams on the backside of the shorts are not flat, and just with trying them on they were a bit uncomfortable. I fear they would rub on long rides. Sadly, I will likely be returning these.
review.name: Worried about the seams

review.reviewBody: I sized up as recommended and the shorts fit comfortably around the waist, upper thighs. They seem well made. However, the band/leg gripper is way too loose. I can't tell if this particular short is defective or if this short is really made for taller women. I'm 5'4.
review.name: Nice but odd fit

review.reviewBody: I sized up after reading the other reviews and it was a good thing that I did. I normally wear a small in Gore but ordered a medium and they were perfect. 5?8? 125 pounds. The chamois Is perfect for me. According to their size chart I should have ordered a small but the medium was perfect.
review.name: My new favorites but run small.

review.reviewBody: 5'6" 120 lbs. 100+ miles/ week. These shorts should be great, as the fit is perfect.  Ordered 1 size up as I am normally a small in other manufacturers.  The narrowness in the front part of the chamois is a nice advantage as too much chamois seems to be the case for most shorts and I don't tolerate a lot of bulk in the hot summer months. review.itemreviewed: Transport Chukka GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: Avid hiker and a big fan of Hokas...I purchased a pair of "Transport GTX" (low cut) maybe (2) years ago and really like them. My only concern was they didn't make a version in "WIDE" so I reached out to HOKA and they suggested that I should bump up my normal size of 11.0W to a 11.5D. I did and the shoe fit great, comfortable & light plus when clean looked great. So when HOKA came out with the "Transport Chukka GTX" (high cut) version I was all over them. My thought was since I have the Transport GTX 11.5D I'll order the same size. Didn't fit way to big & wide and by far the cheapest insoles of any HOKAS I have. I do like the style etc. so exchanging them for my normal size of 11.0 hopefully they fit. Great looking shoe....insoles totally suck.
review.name: Maybe

review.itemreviewed: Transport Chukka GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I was going to buy chuka boots for casual wear, but when I saw these Hokas, they looked like Chaka boots, but they were also sneakers, so I sort of got my chuka boots and another pair of Hokas. Best of both worlds
review.name: Better than chuka boots

review.itemreviewed: Transport Chukka GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: How can such a quality product have soles that look like this. Every part of the black sole including the toe guard has what I can best describe as a white overspray. It does not rub off. I am not talking about a few spots, they are completely covered.
review.name: Not made like this.

review.itemreviewed: Transport Chukka GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I use it for my daily wear. It does not have the amount of support that previous Hokas have.
review.name: I probably would not buy this particular shoe again.

review.itemreviewed: Transport Chukka GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I just ordered these, tried them on, and sent them back. They didn't have the usual Hoka sole, and didn't feel quite right on my feet, unfortunately - none of that cushy propulsive feel that I love about my other 8 pair of Hokas. They looked fine, if not exceptional.
review.name: My least favorite Hokas...

review.itemreviewed: Transport Chukka GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: Shoe is great but need to get different insoles for the shoe. Feel like a cheap insert for such an expensive shoe.
review.name: Love the design but not insoles

review.itemreviewed: Transport Chukka GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I love this new ankle high shoe. I selected it for the materials and wet winter conditions. I'm enjoying the elastic no-tie laces but appreciate that conventional laces are included for those that may not. I'm a 75 YO senior that benefits from the support these shoes provide for the fifteen miles per week I walk and find these so comfy.
